{"title_page": "Blended threat", "text_new": "{{short description|Software exploit combining attacks against different vulnerabilities}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n}}\nA '''blended threat''' (also known as a '''blended attack'''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chien, Sz\u00f6r|first=Eric, P\u00e9ter|date=2002|title=Blended Attacks Exploits, Vulnerabilities and Buffer-Overflow Techniques in Computer Viruses|url=https://www.symantec.com/avcenter/reference/blended.attacks.pdf|journal=Virus Bulletin|volume=|pages=35|via=Symantec Security Response}}</ref>) is a [[software exploit]] which involves a combination of attacks against different [[vulnerability (computing)|vulnerabilities]]. Blended threats can be a combination of [[computer worm|worms]], [[trojan horse (computing)|trojan horses]], and [[computer virus|computer viruses]], all pieces of software that exploit multiple techniques to attack and propagate. A blended threat is a natural, accidental, or purposeful physical or cyber danger that has or indicates the potential to have crossover impacts and harm life, information, operations, the environment, and/or property.\n\nComplex threats consist of two or more distinct attacks aimed at a common target. These can be multiple attacks of the same kind \u2013 a series of coordinated hostilities, as seen in the Paris terrorist attacks in 2015 \u2013 or they could involve varying methods of threat, such as a cyberattack and a distinct physical attack, which may or may not be coordinated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nIn more recent years, as cyber attacks have demonstrated increased ability to impact physical systems, such as [[Stuxnet]] and Triton<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fireeye.com/blog/threat-research/2017/12/attackers-deploy-new-ics-attack-framework-triton.html|title=Attackers Deploy New ICS Attack Framework \"TRITON\" and Cause Operational Disruption to Critical Infrastructure |website=FireEye|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> / Trisis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dragos.com/blog/trisis/|title=TRISIS - Analyzing Safety System Targeted Malware|website=dragos.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> malware, or have caused ransomware outbreaks, such as [[WannaCry ransomware attack|WannaCry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kaspersky.com/blog/wannacry-for-b2b/16544/|title=WannaCry: What you need to know|last=Lab|first=Kaspersky|website=www.kaspersky.com|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> Further recognizing the threats to cyber systems that exist from potential physical hazards, the term blended threat has also been defined as a natural, accidental or purposeful physical or cyber danger that has or indicates the potential to have crossover impacts and harm life, information, operations, the environment, and/or property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|website=gate15.global|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-update-1-1-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats (update 1.1.): Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|website=gate15.global|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref> This is an adaptation based on terminology from the 2010 US Department of Homeland Security's Risk Lexicon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhs.gov/dhs-risk-lexicon|title=DHS Risk Lexicon|date=2009-07-06|work=Department of Homeland Security|access-date=2018-02-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a worst case scenario, The Guardian summarized that hackers could carry out 'cyber-physical attacks', turning satellite antennas into weapons that operate, essentially, like microwave ovens.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/reversemode?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor|title=Ruben Santamarta (@reversemode) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackhat.com/us-18/speakers/Ruben-Santamarta.html|title=Black Hat USA 2018|website=www.blackhat.com|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/news-blog/2018/aug/09/satellite-system-hacking-attacks-ships-planes-military|title=Hacked satellite systems could launch microwave-like attacks, expert warns|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=2018-08-09|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 September 2019, the Cyber Threat Alliance (CTA) released a new Joint Analysis product titled, \u201cThe Illicit Cryptocurrency Threat.\u201d Mining had become an increasing threat in that year, often assessed{{By whom|date=April 2020}} as having overtaken ransomware as the biggest cyber threat to businesses. In their summary of the threat, the CTA claimed that mining attacks had gone from almost nonexistent to being one of the most common attacks their clients encounter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyberthreatalliance.org/joint-analysis-on-illicit-cryptocurrency-mining/|title=They\u2019re Drinking Your Milkshake: CTA\u2019s Joint Analysis on Illicit Cryptocurrency Mining|date=2018-09-19|website=Cyber Threat Alliance|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nFurther, blended threats can compromise the healthcare system. Hospitals, health care, and medical tools and devices all rely on each other. Many health care systems connect to the internet to operate, the same holds true with numerous medical devices such as pacemakers. But that makes the latter part of the \u2018Internet of Things,\u2019 a growing collection of connected devices which are potentially vulnerable to cyberattack. In fact, there have already been reports of threats to these medical devices. Just last year, the FBI recalled half a million pacemakers, as a crucial flaw was discovered that could expose users to an attack. Additionally, security researchers recently revealed a chain of vulnerabilities in a particular pacemaker brand that an attacker could exploit to control implanted pacemakers remotely and cause physical harm to patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of computer viruses and worms]]\n* [[Comparison of computer viruses]]\n* [[List of trojan horses]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mcafeeb2b.com/common/media/mcafeeb2b/us/products/pdf/wp_us_blended_threats.pdf McAfee whitepaper on blended threats][https://web.archive.org/web/20060505030819/http://www.mcafee.com/common/media/mcafeeb2b/us/products/pdf/wp_us_blended_threats.pdf]\n\n[[Category:Computer security exploits]]\n[[Category:Types of malware]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Software exploit combining attacks against different vulnerabilities}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n}}\nA '''blended threat''' (also known as a '''blended attack'''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chien, Sz\u00f6r|first=Eric, P\u00e9ter|date=2002|title=Blended Attacks Exploits, Vulnerabilities and Buffer-Overflow Techniques in Computer Viruses|url=https://www.symantec.com/avcenter/reference/blended.attacks.pdf|journal=Virus Bulletin|volume=|pages=35|via=Symantec Security Response}}</ref>) is a [[software exploit]] which involves a combination of attacks against different [[vulnerability (computing)|vulnerabilities]]. Blended threats can be a combination of [[computer worm|worms]], [[trojan horse (computing)|trojan horses]], and [[computer virus|computer viruses]], all pieces of software that exploit multiple techniques to attack and propagate. A blended threat is a natural, accidental, or purposeful physical or cyber danger that has or indicates the potential to have crossover impacts and harm life, information, operations, the environment, and/or property.\n\nComplex threats consist of two or more distinct attacks aimed at a common target. These can be multiple attacks of the same kind \u2013 a series of coordinated hostilities, as seen in the Paris terrorist attacks in 2015 \u2013 or they could involve varying methods of threat, such as a cyberattack and a distinct physical attack, which may or may not be coordinated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nIn more recent years, as cyber attacks have demonstrated increased ability to impact physical systems, such as [[Stuxnet]] and Triton<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fireeye.com/blog/threat-research/2017/12/attackers-deploy-new-ics-attack-framework-triton.html|title=Attackers Deploy New ICS Attack Framework \"TRITON\" and Cause Operational Disruption to Critical Infrastructure |website=FireEye|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> / Trisis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dragos.com/blog/trisis/|title=TRISIS - Analyzing Safety System Targeted Malware|website=dragos.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> malware, or have caused ransomware outbreaks, such as [[WannaCry ransomware attack|WannaCry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kaspersky.com/blog/wannacry-for-b2b/16544/|title=WannaCry: What you need to know|last=Lab|first=Kaspersky|website=www.kaspersky.com|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> Further recognizing the threats to cyber systems that exist from potential physical hazards, the term blended threat has also been defined as a natural, accidental or purposeful physical or cyber danger that has or indicates the potential to have crossover impacts and harm life, information, operations, the environment, and/or property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|website=gate15.global|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-update-1-1-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats (update 1.1.): Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|website=gate15.global|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref> This is an adaptation based on terminology from the 2010 US Department of Homeland Security's Risk Lexicon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhs.gov/dhs-risk-lexicon|title=DHS Risk Lexicon|date=2009-07-06|work=Department of Homeland Security|access-date=2018-02-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a worst case scenario, The Guardian summarized that hackers could carry out \"'cyber-physical attacks', turning satellite antennas into weapons that operate, essentially, like microwave ovens.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/reversemode?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor|title=Ruben Santamarta (@reversemode) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackhat.com/us-18/speakers/Ruben-Santamarta.html|title=Black Hat USA 2018|website=www.blackhat.com|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/news-blog/2018/aug/09/satellite-system-hacking-attacks-ships-planes-military|title=Hacked satellite systems could launch microwave-like attacks, expert warns|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=2018-08-09|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 September 2019, the Cyber Threat Alliance (CTA) released a new Joint Analysis product titled, \u201cThe Illicit Cryptocurrency Threat.\u201d Mining had become an increasing threat in that year, often assessed{{By whom|date=April 2020}} as having overtaken ransomware as the biggest cyber threat to businesses. In their summary of the threat, the CTA claimed that mining attacks had gone from almost nonexistent to being one of the most common attacks their clients encounter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyberthreatalliance.org/joint-analysis-on-illicit-cryptocurrency-mining/|title=They\u2019re Drinking Your Milkshake: CTA\u2019s Joint Analysis on Illicit Cryptocurrency Mining|date=2018-09-19|website=Cyber Threat Alliance|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nFurther, blended threats can compromise the healthcare system. Hospitals, health care, and medical tools and devices all rely on each other. Many health care systems connect to the internet to operate, the same holds true with numerous medical devices such as pacemakers. But that makes the latter part of the \u2018Internet of Things,\u2019 a growing collection of connected devices which are potentially vulnerable to cyberattack. In fact, there have already been reports of threats to these medical devices. Just last year, the FBI recalled half a million pacemakers, as a crucial flaw was discovered that could expose users to an attack. Additionally, security researchers recently revealed a chain of vulnerabilities in a particular pacemaker brand that an attacker could exploit to control implanted pacemakers remotely and cause physical harm to patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of computer viruses and worms]]\n* [[Comparison of computer viruses]]\n* [[List of trojan horses]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mcafeeb2b.com/common/media/mcafeeb2b/us/products/pdf/wp_us_blended_threats.pdf McAfee whitepaper on blended threats][https://web.archive.org/web/20060505030819/http://www.mcafee.com/common/media/mcafeeb2b/us/products/pdf/wp_us_blended_threats.pdf]\n\n[[Category:Computer security exploits]]\n[[Category:Types of malware]]\n", "name_user": "JDoots", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed extra double quotation mark", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blended_threat"}
{"title_page": "Peats Ferry Bridge", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| bridge_name      = Peats Ferry Bridge\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Hawkesbury River road bridges.jpg\n| image_size       = 280\n| alt              = \n| caption          = The Peats Ferry Bridge, pictured to the right,<br/>carries the [[Pacific Highway (Australia)|Old Pacific Highway]] (B83).<br/>The [[Brooklyn Bridge (Sydney)|Brooklyn Bridge]] on the left carries the [[Pacific Motorway (Sydney\u2013Newcastle)|Pacific Motorway]] (M1), as they both cross the [[Hawkesbury River]]\n| pushpin_map         = New South Wales\n| pushpin_relief      = 1\n| pushpin_map_size    = 280\n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in [[New South Wales]]\n| official_name    = \n| other_name       = \n| carries          = [[Pacific Highway (Australia)|Old Pacific Highway]] {{AUshield|NSW|B83}} {{bulleted list|[[Motor vehicle]]s|[[Pedestrian]]s|[[Bicycle]]s}}\n| crosses          = [[Hawkesbury River]]\n| locale           = {{NSWcity|Brooklyn}}, [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| starts              = {{NSWcity|Kangaroo Point}} (south)\n| ends                = {{NSWcity|Mooney Mooney}} Point (north)\n| owner            = [[Roads & Maritime Services]]\n| maint            = \n| id               =\n| id_type          =  \n| website          = \n| architect        = \n| builder          = Balgue Constructions Pty. Ltd.\n| designer         = [[Department of Main Roads (New South Wales)|NSW Department of Main Roads]]\n| engineering      = Mr. A. R. Shepley\n| winner           = \n| contracted_designer = \n| design           = [[Truss bridge]]\n| material         = [[Steel]]\n| length           = {{convert|2005|ft|6|in|m|0|order=flip}}<!-- (1x43=43)+(2x440=880)+(8x90=720)+(8x40=320)=1963 plus abutments and spacers - engineering docs say 2005ft and SMH 195 say 2010ft -->\n| width            = {{convert|36|ft|m|0|order=flip}} road plus footpath\n| height           = \n| mainspan         = {{convert|440|ft|m|0|order=flip}}\n| number_spans     = 2 main 16 approach\n| pierswater       = 2 / 15 \n| load             = \n| clearance        = \n| clearance_below  = {{convert|70|ft|m|0|order=flip}}\n| depth            = {{convert|241|ft|4|in|m|0|order=flip}}\n| life             = \n| fabricator       = [[Clyde Engineering]]\n| begin            = {{start date|1938|09|01|df=y}}\n| complete         = {{end date|1945|||df=y}}\n| cost             = [[Australian pound|A\u00a3]]454,000\n| open             = 4 April 1945\n| inaugurated      = 6 May 1945\n| named_for        = George Peat / Peats Ferry\n| toll             = \n| traffic          = \n| preceded         = \n| followed         = \n| replaces         = Peats Ferry\n| replaced_by      = [[Brooklyn Bridge (Sydney)|Brooklyn Bridge]]<br />([[Pacific Motorway (Sydney\u2013Newcastle)|Pacific Motorway]]{{spaced endash}} concurrent use)\n| heritage         = NSW State Heritage Register;<br/>[[Roads & Maritime Services]] heritage and conservation register \n| collapsed        = \n| closed           = \n| map_cue          = \n| map_image        = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_text         = \n| map_width        = \n| coordinates      = {{Coord|33.5385|S|151.1993|E|region:AU-NSW_type:landmark|format=dms|display=it}}\n| extra            = \n| references       = <ref name=rmsheritage/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27930851 |title=HAWKESBURY ROAD BRIDGE OPENING |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=33,466 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=28 March 1945 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17873291 |title=PEAT'S FERRY |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=33,115 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=12 February 1944 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=smh>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27934230 |title=Hawkesbury River Bridge Opened |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=33,500 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=7 May 1945 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article223544829 |title=EDITORIAL |newspaper=Construction |volume=LV |issue=1931 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=4 April 1945 |page=1,12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=con>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article223545052 |title=Peat's Ferry Bridge Opened to Traffic |newspaper=Construction |volume=LV |issue=1936 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=10 May 1945 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author1=Fraser, Don |title=NOMINATION REPORT  for the  PEATS FERRY BRIDGE |url=https://portal.engineersaustralia.org.au/system/files/engineering-heritage-australia/nomination-title/Peats%20Ferry%20Bridge%20-%20Nomination.pdf |website=Engineers Australia |date=October 2004}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Peats Ferry Bridge''' is a [[steel]] [[truss bridge]] that carries the [[Pacific Highway (Australia)|Old Pacific Highway]] (B83) across the [[Hawkesbury River]], between {{NSWcity|Kangaroo Point}} and [[Mooney Mooney]] Point, located {{convert|40|km}} north of [[Sydney]] in [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]. The bridge carries the {{NSWcity|Hornsby}} to {{NSWcity|Kariong}} section of highway, while the adjacent [[Brooklyn Bridge (Sydney)|Brooklyn Bridge]] carries the [[Pacific Motorway (Sydney\u2013Newcastle)|Pacific Motorway]] (M1).\n\nThe Peats Ferry Bridge is a single [[carriageway]] with one lane in each direction in [[Highways in Australia|state highway]] conditions; and permits the carriage of [[motor vehicle]]s, [[pedestrian]]s and [[bicycle]]s. The adjacent Brooklyn Bridge is a [[dual carriageway]] with three lanes in each direction of [[motorway]] [[grade separation|grade-separated]] conditions. Both bridges are maintained by [[Roads & Maritime Services|NSW Roads & Maritime Services]].\n\n==History==\nPeats Ferry, a [[ferry]] operated by George Peat from 1847 until the 1890s, provided a local crossing of the Hawkesbury River: at that time there was no direct road between Sydney and Newcastle. The ferry service was made redundant by the completion of the [[Central Coast & Newcastle Line|Sydney-Newcastle railway]] in 1889 with the opening of the first Hawkesbury River railway bridge. Between 1925 and 1930 the New South Wales Public Works Department, and subsequently the Main Roads Board, undertook construction of the road between Hornsby and Gosford, in order to provide a direct road route between Sydney and Newcastle. Upon completion of the roadworks in 1930 Peats Ferry was reinstated between Kangaroo Point and Mooney Mooney Point, pending construction of the bridge.\n\nConstruction of the bridge commenced in 1938 but it was not completed until May 1945.<ref name=rmsheritage>{{Cite NSW HD|4309666|Peats Ferry Road Bridge over Hawkesbury River|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite NSW HD|1780040|Peats Ferry Road Bridge |access-date=}}</ref> Prior to construction of the Hornsby-Gosford road via Peats ferry the most direct road route between Sydney and Newcastle was via the Old Northern Road via Wisemans Ferry and Cessnock, built in the 1820s.\n\nThe Sydney-Hornsby-Gosford-Newcastle route was named as part of the Great Northern Highway in 1928, and renamed as part of the Pacific Highway in 1931.\n\n==Description==\nThe two main bridge spans are K-trusses of welded steel construction. Each truss span measures {{convert|130|m|ft}} long and these were the longest welded truss spans in the world when built. The deck of the truss spans in concrete, cast [[in situ]] around the truss members. The truss spans were fabricated off site and floated into position on barges, requiring a high degree of accuracy and coordination in fabrication and bridge pier setting out. To the north of the truss spans, the bridge has eight long and eight short steel girder spans. The bridge deck to these spans is also cast in situ concrete but is believed not to act compositely with steel, as might be used in more modern construction.<ref name=rmsheritage/>\n\nNorth of the bridge itself a causeway some {{convert|220|m|ft|0}} long was built in shallow water to complete the link to the northern bank.\n\nThe Pier supporting the main bridge spans is founded on a concrete caisson. The cutting foot of the caisson was cast on a barge in sheltered water and then floated out and sunk to the river bed within its own cofferdam. Jetting with compressed air and the addition of further sections of caisson then further sank the caisson. At one point the caisson accidentally slid under its own weight to below the water line. To recover this situation a further section had to be added by divers and the caisson pumped out, which took nine months to complete. The final caisson extends {{convert|73.56|m|ft}} below low water level, just {{convert|20|cm|in|}} short of the world record depth for a bridge foundation at that time, held by the [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge]].<ref name=rmsheritage/>\n\nThe bridge abutments are cast in situ concrete bearing to rock. Each abutment has concrete walls and parapets (balustrades).<ref name=rmsheritage/>\n\nThe original railings to the east and west sides of the bridge spans were tubular top and bottom rails supported to steel angle standards with crimped wire mesh infill panels. These original rails still exist to the girder spans of the bridge. The rails to the two truss spans of the bridge were modified in 1966 by the removal of the tubular rails and crimped wire mesh and substitution with Armco type barriers bolted to the original steel angle standards. This was done in conjunction with the reconfiguration of the lanes to provide a third lane for tidal flow arrangements.\n\nThe bridge has two plaques at its south abutment commemorating the opening of the bridge in 1945 and the \"energy and skill of its builders\".<ref name=rmsheritage/> A [[toll road|toll]] was levied on crossing the bridge, payable at the Mooney Mooney Point end of the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |format=photo |author= |url=https://hornsbyshire.recollect.net.au/nodes/view/1624 |title=Toll barriers at Mooney Mooney Point, Hawkesbury River Road Bridge |work=Recollects |publisher=[[Hornsby Shire Council]] |date=1949 |access-date=6 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was superseded as the main crossing of the Hawkesbury River at this point by the opening of the adjacent six-lane [[motorway]] bridge as part of the fourth stage of the Pacific Motorway in 1973. It continues in service carrying the Pacific Highway route as a backup and alternative route to the motorway, and provides access from the motorway to the towns of Brooklyn and Mooney Mooney, and to Mount White.\n\n==Heritage significance==\n{{quotation|''Peat's Ferry Road Bridge is of State significance owing to its historical associations and technical and engineering qualities. It was constructed between 1938 and 1945 and the current bridge fabric is original to the 1945 construction. The original parapets, however, have been partly removed and have had Armco barriers added over the truss span lengths. The bridge is at the site of the ferry crossing first established by George Peat in 1847. From 1945 until 1980s, when the Sydney to Newcastle Freeway was built, the current bridge provided a direct and vital link from Sydney to the industrial north.''|Statement of significance, Heritage and conservation register, [[Roads & Maritime Services]], 15 August 2005.<ref name=rmsheritage/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Transport|Engineering|New South Wales|Australian roads}}}}\n* [[List of bridges in Sydney]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Cite web|author=Kass, Terry|title=RTA Thematic History: A component of the RTA Heritage and Conservation Register|url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/about/environment/thematic-history-rta2006.pdf|type=PDF|work=[[Roads & Maritime Services|NSW Roads & Maritime Services]]|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]]|date=February 2006|edition=2nd |accessdate=12 January 2015}}\n\n{{Bridges in Sydney |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Road infrastructure in Sydney |state=autocollapse}}\n{{The Hawkesbury River |state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Pacific Highway (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Hawkesbury River]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in Australia]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1945]]\n[[Category:1945 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Truss bridges in Australia]]\n[[Category:Transport on the Central Coast (New South Wales)]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in New South Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| bridge_name      = Peats Ferry Bridge\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Hawkesbury River road bridges.jpg\n| image_size       = 280\n| alt              = \n| caption          = The Peats Ferry Bridge, pictured to the right,<br/>carries the [[Pacific Highway (Australia)|Pacific Highway]].<br/>The [[Brooklyn Bridge (Sydney)|Brooklyn Bridge]] on the left carries the [[Pacific Motorway (Sydney\u2013Newcastle)|Pacific Motorway]], as they both cross the [[Hawkesbury River]]\n| official_name    = \n| other_name       = \n| carries          = [[Pacific Highway (Australia)|Pacific Highway]];<br/>{{smaller|(Road traffic, pedestrians, bicycles)}}\n| crosses          = [[Hawkesbury River]]\n| locale           = {{NSWcity|Brooklyn}}, [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| owner            = [[Roads & Maritime Services]]\n| maint            = \n| id               =\n| id_type          =  \n| website          = \n| architect        = \n| builder          = Balgue Constructions Pty. Ltd.\n| designer         = [[Department of Main Roads (New South Wales)|NSW Department of Main Roads]]\n| engineering      = Mr. A. R. Shepley\n| winner           = \n| contracted_designer = \n| design           = [[Truss bridge]]\n| material         = [[Steel]]\n| length           = {{convert|2005|ft|6|in|m|0|order=flip}}<ref>{{Cite web |author1=Fraser, Don |title=NOMINATION REPORT  for the  PEATS FERRY BRIDGE |url=https://portal.engineersaustralia.org.au/system/files/engineering-heritage-australia/nomination-title/Peats%20Ferry%20Bridge%20-%20Nomination.pdf |website=Engineers Australia |date=October 2004}}</ref><ref name=con/><!-- (1x43=43)+(2x440=880)+(8x90=720)+(8x40=320)=1963 plus abutments and spacers - engineering docs say 2005ft and SMH 195 say 2010ft -->\n| width            = {{convert|36|ft|m|0|order=flip}} road plus footpath\n| height           = \n| mainspan         = {{convert|440|ft|m|0|order=flip}}\n| number_spans     = 2 main 16 approach\n| pierswater       = 2 / 15 \n| load             = \n| clearance        = \n| clearance_below  = {{convert|70|ft|m|0|order=flip}}\n| depth            = {{convert|241|ft|4|in|m|0|order=flip}}\n| life             = \n| fabricator       = [[Clyde Engineering]] (bridge)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article223544829 |title=EDITORIAL |newspaper=Construction |volume=LV |issue=1931 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=4 April 1945 |page=1,12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n| begin            = {{start date|1938|09|01|df=y}}\n| complete         = {{end date|1945|||df=y}}\n| cost             = \u00a3454,000<ref name=smh /><ref name=con>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article223545052 |title=Peat's Ferry Bridge Opened to Traffic |newspaper=Construction |volume=LV |issue=1936 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=10 May 1945 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n| open             = 4 April 1945\n| inaugurated      = 6 May 1945\n| named_for        = George Peat / Peats Ferry\n| toll             = \n| traffic          = \n| preceded         = \n| followed         = \n| replaces         = Peats Ferry\n| replaced_by      = [[Brooklyn Bridge (Sydney)|Brooklyn Bridge]]<br />([[Pacific Motorway (Sydney\u2013Newcastle)|Pacific Motorway]]{{spaced endash}}{{smaller|concurrent use}})\n| heritage         = NSW State Heritage Register;<br/>[[Roads & Maritime Services]] heritage and conservation register \n| collapsed        = \n| closed           = \n| map_cue          = \n| map_image        = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_text         = \n| map_width        = \n| coordinates      = {{Coord|33.5385|S|151.1993|E|region:AU-NSW_type:landmark|format=dms|display=it}}\n| extra            = \n| references       = <ref name=rmsheritage/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27930851 |title=HAWKESBURY ROAD BRIDGE OPENING |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=33,466 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=28 March 1945 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17873291 |title=PEAT'S FERRY |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=33,115 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=12 February 1944 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=smh>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27934230 |title=Hawkesbury River Bridge Opened |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=33,500 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=7 May 1945 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Peats Ferry Bridge''' is a [[steel]] [[truss bridge]] that carries the [[Pacific Highway (Australia)|Pacific Highway]] across the [[Hawkesbury River]], between {{NSWcity|Kangaroo Point}} and [[Mooney Mooney]] Point, located {{convert|40|km}} north of [[Sydney]] in [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]. The bridge carries the {{NSWcity|Hornsby}} to {{NSWcity|Kariong}} section of highway, while the adjacent [[Brooklyn Bridge (Sydney)|Brooklyn Bridge]] carries the [[Pacific Motorway (Sydney\u2013Newcastle)|Pacific Motorway]] (M1).\n\nThe Peats Ferry Bridge is a single [[carriageway]] with one lane in each direction in [[Highways in Australia|state highway]] conditions; and permits the carriage of [[motor vehicle]]s, [[pedestrian]]s and [[bicycle]]s. The adjacent Brooklyn Bridge is a [[dual carriageway]] with three lanes in each direction of [[motorway]] [[grade separation|grade-separated]] conditions. Both bridges are maintained by [[Roads & Maritime Services|NSW Roads & Maritime Services]].\n\n==History==\nPeats Ferry, a [[ferry]] operated by George Peat from 1847 until the 1890s, provided a local crossing of the Hawkesbury River: at that time there was no direct road between Sydney and Newcastle. The ferry service was made redundant by the completion of the [[Central Coast & Newcastle Line|Sydney-Newcastle railway]] in 1889 with the opening of the first Hawkesbury River railway bridge. Between 1925 and 1930 the New South Wales Public Works Department, and subsequently the Main Roads Board, undertook construction of the road between Hornsby and Gosford, in order to provide a direct road route between Sydney and Newcastle. Upon completion of the roadworks in 1930 Peats Ferry was reinstated between Kangaroo Point and Mooney Mooney Point, pending construction of the bridge.\n\nConstruction of the bridge commenced in 1938 but it was not completed until May 1945.<ref name=rmsheritage>{{Cite NSW HD|4309666|Peats Ferry Road Bridge over Hawkesbury River (SGOV)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite NSW HD|1780040|Peats Ferry Road Bridge (LGOV)}}</ref> Prior to construction of the Hornsby-Gosford road via Peats ferry the most direct road route between Sydney and Newcastle was via the Old Northern Road via Wisemans Ferry and Cessnock, built in the 1820s.\n\nThe Sydney-Hornsby-Gosford-Newcastle route was named as part of the Great Northern Highway in 1928, and renamed as part of the Pacific Highway in 1931.\n\n==Description==\nThe two main bridge spans are K-trusses of welded steel construction. Each truss span measures {{convert|130|m|ft}} long and these were the longest welded truss spans in the world when built. The deck of the truss spans in concrete, cast [[in situ]] around the truss members. The truss spans were fabricated off site and floated into position on barges, requiring a high degree of accuracy and coordination in fabrication and bridge pier setting out. To the north of the truss spans, the bridge has eight long and eight short steel girder spans. The bridge deck to these spans is also cast in situ concrete but is believed not to act compositely with steel, as might be used in more modern construction.<ref name=rmsheritage/>\n\nNorth of the bridge itself a causeway some {{convert|220|m|ft|0}} long was built in shallow water to complete the link to the northern bank.\n\nThe Pier supporting the main bridge spans is founded on a concrete caisson. The cutting foot of the caisson was cast on a barge in sheltered water and then floated out and sunk to the river bed within its own cofferdam. Jetting with compressed air and the addition of further sections of caisson then further sank the caisson. At one point the caisson accidentally slid under its own weight to below the water line. To recover this situation a further section had to be added by divers and the caisson pumped out, which took nine months to complete. The final caisson extends {{convert|73.56|m|ft}} below low water level, just {{convert|20|cm|in|}} short of the world record depth for a bridge foundation at that time, held by the [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge]].<ref name=rmsheritage/>\n\nThe bridge abutments are cast in situ concrete bearing to rock. Each abutment has concrete walls and parapets (balustrades).<ref name=rmsheritage/>\n\nThe original railings to the east and west sides of the bridge spans were tubular top and bottom rails supported to steel angle standards with crimped wire mesh infill panels. These original rails still exist to the girder spans of the bridge. The rails to the two truss spans of the bridge were modified in 1966 by the removal of the tubular rails and crimped wire mesh and substitution with Armco type barriers bolted to the original steel angle standards. This was done in conjunction with the reconfiguration of the lanes to provide a third lane for tidal flow arrangements.\n\nThe bridge has two plaques at its south abutment commemorating the opening of the bridge in 1945 and the \"energy and skill of its builders\".<ref name=rmsheritage/> A [[toll road|toll]] was levied on crossing the bridge, payable at the Mooney Mooney Point end of the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |format=photo |author= |url=https://hornsbyshire.recollect.net.au/nodes/view/1624 |title=Toll barriers at Mooney Mooney Point, Hawkesbury River Road Bridge |work=Recollects |publisher=[[Hornsby Shire Council]] |date=1949 |access-date=6 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was superseded as the main crossing of the Hawkesbury River at this point by the opening of the adjacent six-lane [[motorway]] bridge as part of the fourth stage of the Pacific Motorway in 1973. It continues in service carrying the Pacific Highway route as a backup and alternative route to the motorway, and provides access from the motorway to the towns of Brooklyn and Mooney Mooney, and to Mount White.\n\n==Heritage significance==\n{{quotation|''Peat's Ferry Road Bridge is of State significance owing to its historical associations and technical and engineering qualities. It was constructed between 1938 and 1945 and the current bridge fabric is original to the 1945 construction. The original parapets, however, have been partly removed and have had Armco barriers added over the truss span lengths. The bridge is at the site of the ferry crossing first established by George Peat in 1847. From 1945 until 1980s, when the Sydney to Newcastle Freeway was built, the current bridge provided a direct and vital link from Sydney to the industrial north.''|Statement of significance, Heritage and conservation register, [[Roads & Maritime Services]], 15 August 2005.<ref name=rmsheritage/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Transport|Engineering}}}}\n* [[List of bridges in Sydney]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Cite web|author=Kass, Terry|title=RTA Thematic History: A component of the RTA Heritage and Conservation Register|url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/about/environment/thematic-history-rta2006.pdf|type=PDF|work=[[Roads & Maritime Services|NSW Roads & Maritime Services]]|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]]|date=February 2006|edition=2nd |accessdate=12 January 2015}}\n\n{{Bridges in Sydney |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Road infrastructure in Sydney |state=autocollapse}}\n{{The Hawkesbury River |state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Pacific Highway (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Hawkesbury River]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in Australia]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1945]]\n[[Category:1945 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Truss bridges in Australia]]\n[[Category:Transport on the Central Coast (New South Wales)]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in New South Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Rangasyd", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove {{tl|small}} as per MOS; move refs together; add map; general clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peats_Ferry_Bridge"}
{"title_page": "Rajnath Singh", "text_new": "{{short description|Defence Minister of India}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Rajnath Singh\n| image = Defence Minister Shri Rajnath Singh in February 2020.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Singh in 2020\n| office = [[Minister of Defence (India)|Minister of Defence]]\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| term_start = 31 May 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Nirmala Sitharaman]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Minister of Home Affairs]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| term_start1 = 26 May 2014\n| term_end1 = 30 May 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Sushilkumar Shinde]]\n| successor1 = [[Amit Shah]]\n| term_start2 = 24 January 2013\n| term_end2 = 8 July 2014\n| predecessor2 = [[Nitin Gadkari]]\n| successor2 = [[Amit Shah]]\n| office2 = [[List of presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President of the Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| term_start3 = 31 December 2005\n| term_end3 = 19 December 2009\n| predecessor3 = [[L. K. Advani]]\n| successor3 = [[Nitin Gadkari]]\n| office4 = [[Minister of Agriculture (India)|Minister of Agriculture]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| term_start4 = 24 May 2003\n| term_end4 = 22 May 2004\n| predecessor4 = [[Ajit Singh (politician)|Ajit Singh]]\n| successor4 = [[Sharad Pawar]]\n| office5 = 19th [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh]]\n| governor5 = [[Suraj Bhan]]<br />[[Vishnu Kant Shastri]]\n| term_start5 = 28 October 2000\n| term_end5 = 8 March 2002\n| predecessor5 = [[Ram Prakash Gupta]]\n| successor5 = [[President's rule]]\n| office6 = [[Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha]]\n| constituency6 = [[Lucknow (Lok Sabha constituency)|Lucknow]]\n| term_start6 = 16 May 2014\n| term_end6 = \n| predecessor6 = [[Lalji Tandon]]\n| successor6 = \n| constituency7 = [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghaziabad]]\n| term_start7 = 16 May 2009\n| term_end7 = 16 May 2014\n| predecessor7 = ''Constituency established''\n| successor7 = [[Vijay Kumar Singh]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|7|10}}\n| birth_place = Bhabhaura, [[Chandauli district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| otherparty = [[Bharatiya Jana Sangh]] <small>(Before 1977)</small>\n| spouse = Savitri Singh\n| children = 3, including [[Pankaj Singh (politician)|Pankaj Singh]]\n| alma_mater = [[Gorakhpur University]] ([[M.Sc.]] in [[Physics]])\n| website = {{url|rajnathsingh.in|Official website}}\n| education = \n}}\n'''Rajnath Singh''' (born 10 July 1951) is an Indian politician serving as the [[Minister of Defence (India)|Defence Minister of India]]. He is the former [[List of presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President]] of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]. He has previously served as the [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|Chief]] [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|Minister]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] and as a [[Union Council of Ministers|Cabinet Minister]] in the [[Vajpayee Government]]. He was the [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Home Minister]] in the [[First Modi ministry|First Modi Ministry]]. He has also served as the [[List of Presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President]] of the BJP twice, 2005 to 2009 and 2013 to 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nSingh was born in Bhabhaura village of [[Chandauli district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. His father was Ram Badan Singh and his mother was Gujarati Devi. He was born into a family of farmers and went on to secure a master's degree in physics, acquiring first division results from the [[Gorakhpur University]]. Rajnath Singh had been associated with the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] since 1964, at the age of 13 and remained connected with the organisation. In 1974, he was appointed secretary for the Mirzapur unit of the [[Bharatiya Jana Sangh]], predecessor of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite news|title=Profile: Rajnath Singh |publisher=[[Zee News]] |url=http://www.zeenews.com/znnew/articles.asp?rep=2&aid=264537&sid=ARC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930185718/http://www.zeenews.com/znnew/articles.asp?rep=2&aid=264537&sid=ARC |archivedate=30 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nIn 1975, aged 24, Singh was appointed District President of the [[Jana Sangh]]. In 1977, he was elected [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of Legislative Assembly]] from the [[Mirzapur]]. He became the State President of the BJP youth wing in 1984, the National general secretary in 1986 and the National President in 1988. He was also elected into the [[Uttar Pradesh]] [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Council|legislative council.]]<ref name=\"profile\"/>\n\nIn 1991, he became Education Minister in the first BJP government in the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Major highlights of his tenure as Education Minister included [[Anti-Copying Act, 1992]], which made copying a non-bailable offence,<ref name=\"rediff1\">[http://www.rediff.com/news/report/how-rajnath-singh-rose-through-the-ranks/20130131.htm \"How Rajnath Singh rose through the ranks\"]. Rediff.com. 31 January 2013</ref> modernising science texts and incorporating [[Indian mathematics#Vedic period|vedic mathematics]] into the [[syllabus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/who-is-rajnath-singh/1/247240.html |title=Who is Rajnath Singh? : India, News|work=India Today |date=23 January 2013 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> In April 1994, he was elected into the [[Rajya Sabha]] (Upper House of the [[Parliament of India|Parliament]]) and he became involved with the Advisory committee on Industry (1994\u201396), Consultative Committee for the Ministry of Agriculture, Business Advisory Committee, House Committee and the Committee on Human Resource Development.<ref name=\"profile\"/> On 25 March 1997, he became the President of the BJP's unit in Uttar Pradesh and in 1999 he became the Union Cabinet Minister for Surface Transport.<ref name=\"profile\" />\n\n=== Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh (2000-02) ===\nIn 2000, he became [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|Chief Minister]] of Uttar Pradesh and was twice elected as MLA from [[Haidergarh (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Haidergarh]] in 2001 and 2002.<ref name=\"rediff1\" /> He tried to rationalise the reservation structure in government jobs by introducing the most Backward Classes among the OBC and SC, so that the benefit of reservation can reach the lowest status of Society.<ref name=achieve>[http://www.rajnathsingh.in/achievements/ \"Achievements\"]. rajnathsingh.in</ref>\n\nOn 7 February 2001, Singh inaugurated the [[DND Flyway]] which connects Delhi to Noida.<ref>{{cite news |title='Noida jinx' to keep Akhilesh Yadav away from PM event |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/noida-jinx-to-keep-akhilesh-yadav-away-from-pm-event/articleshow/50372875.cms |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Union Agriculture Minister (2003-04) ===\nIn 2003, Singh was appointed as the [[Ministry of Agriculture & Farmers Welfare|Minister of Agriculture]] and subsequently for Food Processing in the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|NDA]] Government led by [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], and was faced with the difficult task of maintaining one of the most volatile areas of India's economy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2003/06/11/stories/2003061100100800.htm|title=Courage, Mr Rajnath Singh|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=11 June 2003}}</ref> During this period he initiated a few epoch-making projects including the Kisan Call Centre and Farm Income Insurance Scheme.<ref>[http://wikimapia.org/16811689/Shri-Rajnath-Singh-MP-Loksabh-Ghaziabad-Ex-CM-Uattar-pardesh-1-30-Raj-Nagra \"Shri Rajnath Singh, MP (Ghaziabad)\"]. wikimapia.org</ref> He brought down interest rates on Agriculture loans and also established Farmer Commission and initiated Farms Income Insurance Scheme.<ref name=achieve/>\n\n=== National President of the BJP (2005-09) ===\nAfter the BJP lost power in the [[2004 Indian general election|2004 general elections]], it was forced to sit in the Opposition. After the resignation of prominent figure [[Lal Krishna Advani]], and the murder of strategist [[Pramod Mahajan]], Singh sought to rebuild the party by focusing on the most basic [[Hindutva]] ideologies.<ref name=\"instinct\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-12-23/india/27815843_1_rajnath-singh-uniform-civil-code-bjp-national-executive|title=It's basic instinct for Rajnath Singh|work=[[The Times of India]] | first1=Lopamudra|last1=Ghatak|date=23 December 2006}}</ref> He announced his position of \"no compromise\" in relation to the building of a [[Ram Janmabhoomi|Ram Temple]] in [[Ayodhya]] at any cost<ref name=\"instinct\" /> and commended the rule of Vajpayee as Prime Minister, pointing towards all the developments the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|NDA]] made for the ordinary people of India.<ref>[http://indianewsdiary.com/?p=8951 Rajnath Singh is new BJP President] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140311070147/http://indianewsdiary.com/?p=8951 |date=11 March 2014 }}. indianewsdiary.com</ref> He also criticised the role of the English language in India, claiming that most of Indian population is unable to participate in Indian economy and cultural discourse due to extreme preferences shown to English at the expense of native languages.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/BJP-chief-claims-English-bad-for-India-triggers-outrage/articleshow/21178996.cms \"BJP chief claims English bad for India, triggers outrage.\"] ''The Times of India''. 20 July 2013</ref>\n\nHe became the BJP National President on 31 December 2005, a post he held till 19 December 2009. In May 2009, he was elected MP from Ghaziabad in Uttar Pradesh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/Shri%20Rajnath%20Singh%20Biodata_English.pdf|title=Ministry of Home Affairs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606031010/http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/Shri%20Rajnath%20Singh%20Biodata_English.pdf|archive-date=6 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2013, following the resignation of [[Nitin Gadkari]] due to corruption charges, Singh was re-elected as the BJP's National President.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Press Trust of India |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-12-19/india/28067924_1_rajnath-singh-nitin-gadkari-bjp-president |title=Rajnath steps down, Gadkari takes over as BJP president |work=The Times of India |date=19 December 2009 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nSingh is on record shortly after the law [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]] was re-instated in 2013, claiming that his party is \"unambiguously\" in favour of the law, also claiming that \"We will state (at an all-party meeting if it is called) that we support Section 377 because we believe that homosexuality is an unnatural act and cannot be supported.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1131214/jsp/nation/story_17679913.jsp#.VROkUJOUeHw|title=BJP comes out, vows to oppose homosexuality|last=Rameshan|first=Radhika|date=13 December 2011|website=The Telegraph|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe contested the 2014 Lok Sabha elections from [[Lucknow (Lok Sabha constituency)|Lucknow]] constituency and was subsequently elected as a [[Member of Parliament (India)|Member of the Parliament]].<ref name=\"the hindu\">[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/rajnath-singh-surpasses-vajpayees-victory-margin-in-lucknow/article6021382.ece \"Rajnath Singh surpasses Vajpayee\u2019s victory margin in Lucknow\"]. ''The Hindu''. 18 May 2014</ref>\n\n=== Union Home Minister (2014-19) ===\n[[File:The Union Home Minister, Shri Rajnath Singh reviewing the working of the Border Security Force, in New Delhi (1).jpg|thumb|The Union Home Minister, Shri Rajnath Singh reviewing the working of the Border Security Force, in New Delhi]]\nHe was appointed the [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Union Minister of Home Affairs]] in the [[Narendra Modi]] [[First Modi ministry|government]] and was sworn in on 26 May 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmindia.gov.in/en/news_updates/portfolios-of-the-union-council-of-ministers-2/|title=Portfolios of the Union Council of Ministers|website=www.pmindia.gov.in|accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe triggered controversy amid the protests over the police action at [[Jawaharlal Nehru University, Delhi|Jawaharlal Nehru University]] (JNU), on 14 February 2016, claiming that the \"JNU incident\" was supported by [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] chief Hafiz Saeed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/rajnath-singh-hafiz-saeed-let-jnu-protests-had-support-of-let-chief-hafiz-saeed-rajnath-singh/|title=Understand the reality\u2026 Lashkar chief Hafiz Saeed backed JNU incident: Home Minister Rajnath Singh|date=15 February 2016|accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, he claimed that infiltration from Pakistan declined by 52% in a period of two years.<ref>{{citation |title=Narendra Modi's 56-inch chest not reduced an inch: Rajnath Singh |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/280516/narendra-modi-s-56-inch-chest-not-reduced-an-inch-rajnath-singh.html |work=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |date=28 May 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2017, he launched [[Bharat Ke Veer]] Web portal and Application with Bollywood actor [[Akshay Kumar]]. This was an initiative taken by him for the welfare of Martyrs' family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=160767|title=Shri Rajnath Singh inaugurates Web Portal 'Bharat ke Veer'|website=pib.nic.in|access-date=11 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn official anthem was launched on 20 January 2018 for the cause '[[Bharat Ke Veer]]' by him along with film star [[Akshay Kumar]], and other ministers [[Kiren Rijiju]], [[Hansraj Gangaram Ahir|Hansraj Ahir]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/akshay-kumar-rajnath-singh-unveil-official-anthem-of-bharat-ke-veer/articleshow/62581609.cms|title=Akshay Kumar, Rajnath Singh unveil official anthem of 'Bharat Ke Veer'|date=20 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn  21 May 2018, he commissioned [[Bastariya Battalion]]. As Union Home Minister, Rajnath Singh attended the passing out parade of 241 Bastariya Battalion of [[Central Reserve Police Force|CRPF]] in Ambikapur, Chhattisgarh on 21 May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/first-ever-passing-out-parade-of-bastariya-battalion-held-in-chhattisgarh-1238057-2018-05-21|title=First ever graduation parade of 'Bastariya Battalion' held in Chhattisgarh|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=6 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Union Defence Minister (2019- present)===\n[[File:Defence Minister Rajnath Singh commissions INS Khanderi at Mumbai (7).jpg|thumb|Defence Minister Rajnath Singh commissions INS Khanderi at Mumbai]]\nSingh became the [[Minister of Defence (India)|Defence minister]] of India on 31 May  2019.<ref>{{citation |title=PM Modi allocates portfolios. Full list of new ministers |url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/news/pm-modi-allocates-portfolios-full-list-of-new-ministers-1559288502067.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=31 May 2019 }}</ref><center><gallery widths=\"220\" heights=\"200\">\n</gallery></center> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://164.100.47.194/Loksabha/Members/MemberBioprofile.aspx?mpsno=4268 Biography Profile] at Lok Sabha, Parliament of India\n* [http://rajnathsingh.in/ Official website] (personal)\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Offices and distinctions\n|list1= \n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|in-upr}}\n{{s-bef|before=N/A}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Rajya Sabha]] [[List of Rajya Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh]] |years=1994 \u2013 2001}}\n{{s-aft|after=N/A}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=N/A}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Rajya Sabha]] [[List of Rajya Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh]] |years=2002 \u2013 2008}}\n{{s-aft|after=N/A}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-par|in-lwr}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghaziabad]]|years=2009\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Vijay Kumar Singh]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lalji Tandon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Lucknow (Lok Sabha constituency)|Lucknow]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ram Prakash Gupta]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh]]|years=28 October 2000 \u2013 8 March 2002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mayawati]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ajit Singh (politician)|Ajit Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Agriculture (India)|Union Minister of Agriculture]]|years=24 May 2003 \u2013 22 May 2004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sharad Pawar]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sushilkumar Shinde]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Union Minister of Home Affairs]]|years=26 May 2014 \u2013 30 May 2019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Amit Shah]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nirmala Sitharaman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence (India)|Union Minister of Defence]]|years=31 May 2019 \u2013 present }}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[L. K. Advani]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=National President<br />[[Bharatiya Janata Party]]|years=24 December 2005 \u2013 24 December 2009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nitin Gadkari]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nitin Gadkari]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=National President<br />[[Bharatiya Janata Party]]|years=23 January 2013 \u2013 8 July 2014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Amit Shah]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n}} \n{{Second Narendra Modi Cabinet}}\n{{Cabinet of Narendra Modi}}\n{{Home Ministers of India}}\n{{Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party chief ministers|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Rajnath}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:15th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:16th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Agriculture Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Chief ministers from Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Deen Dayal Upadhyay Gorakhpur University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Internal Affairs of India]]\n[[Category:Narendra Modi ministry]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 1977\u20131980]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 1997\u20132002]]\n[[Category:People from Chandauli district]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Varanasi]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ghaziabad]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Lucknow]]\n[[Category:17th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Alliance candidates in the 2019 Indian general election]]\n[[Category:Defence Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Defence Minister of India}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Rajnath Singh\n| image = Defence Minister Shri Rajnath Singh in February 2020.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Singh in 2020\n| office = [[Minister of Defence (India)|Minister of Defence]]\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| term_start = 31 May 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Nirmala Sitharaman]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Minister of Home Affairs]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| term_start1 = 26 May 2014\n| term_end1 = 30 May 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Sushilkumar Shinde]]\n| successor1 = [[Amit Shah]]\n| term_start2 = 24 January 2013\n| term_end2 = 8 July 2014\n| predecessor2 = [[Nitin Gadkari]]\n| successor2 = [[Amit Shah]]\n| office2 = [[List of presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President of the Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| term_start3 = 31 December 2005\n| term_end3 = 19 December 2009\n| predecessor3 = [[L. K. Advani]]\n| successor3 = [[Nitin Gadkari]]\n| office4 = [[Minister of Agriculture (India)|Minister of Agriculture]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| term_start4 = 24 May 2003\n| term_end4 = 22 May 2004\n| predecessor4 = [[Ajit Singh (politician)|Ajit Singh]]\n| successor4 = [[Sharad Pawar]]\n| office5 = 19th [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh]]\n| governor5 = [[Suraj Bhan]]<br />[[Vishnu Kant Shastri]]\n| term_start5 = 28 October 2000\n| term_end5 = 8 March 2002\n| predecessor5 = [[Ram Prakash Gupta]]\n| successor5 = [[President's rule]]\n| office6 = [[Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha]]\n| constituency6 = [[Lucknow (Lok Sabha constituency)|Lucknow]]\n| term_start6 = 16 May 2014\n| term_end6 = \n| predecessor6 = [[Lalji Tandon]]\n| successor6 = \n| constituency7 = [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghaziabad]]\n| term_start7 = 16 May 2009\n| term_end7 = 16 May 2014\n| predecessor7 = ''Constituency established''\n| successor7 = [[Vijay Kumar Singh]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|7|10}}\n| birth_place = Bhabhaura, [[Chandauli district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| otherparty = [[Bharatiya Jana Sangh]] <small>(Before 1977)</small>\n| spouse = Savitri Singh\n| children = 3, including [[Pankaj Singh (politician)|Pankaj Singh]]\n| alma_mater = [[Gorakhpur University]] ([[M.Sc.]] in [[Physics]])\n| website = {{url|rajnathsingh.in|Official website}}\n| education = \n}}\n'''Rajnath Singh''' (born 10 July 1951) is an Indian politician serving as the [[Minister of Defence (India)|Defence Minister of India]]. He is the former [[List of presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President]] of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]. He has previously served as the [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|Chief]] [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|Minister]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] and as a [[Union Council of Ministers|Cabinet Minister]] in the [[Vajpayee Government]]. He was the [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Home Minister]] in the [[First Modi ministry|First Modi Ministry]]. He has also served as the [[List of Presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President]] of the BJP twice, 2005 to 2009 and 2013 to 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nSingh was born in Bhabhaura village of [[Chandauli district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. His father was Ram Badan Singh and his mother was Gujarati Devi. He was born into a family of farmers and went on to secure a master's degree in physics, acquiring first division results from the [[Gorakhpur University]]. Rajnath Singh had been associated with the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] since 1964, at the age of 13 and remained connected with the organisation. In 1974, he was appointed secretary for the Mirzapur unit of the [[Bharatiya Jana Sangh]], predecessor of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite news|title=Profile: Rajnath Singh |publisher=[[Zee News]] |url=http://www.zeenews.com/znnew/articles.asp?rep=2&aid=264537&sid=ARC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930185718/http://www.zeenews.com/znnew/articles.asp?rep=2&aid=264537&sid=ARC |archivedate=30 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nIn 1975, aged 24, Singh was appointed District President of the [[Jana Sangh]]. In 1977, he was elected [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of Legislative Assembly]] from the [[Mirzapur]]. He became the State President of the BJP youth wing in 1984, the National general secretary in 1986 and the National President in 1988. He was also elected into the [[Uttar Pradesh]] [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Council|legislative council.]]<ref name=\"profile\"/>\n\nIn 1991, he became Education Minister in the first BJP government in the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Major highlights of his tenure as Education Minister included [[Anti-Copying Act, 1992]], which made copying a non-bailable offence,<ref name=\"rediff1\">[http://www.rediff.com/news/report/how-rajnath-singh-rose-through-the-ranks/20130131.htm \"How Rajnath Singh rose through the ranks\"]. Rediff.com. 31 January 2013</ref> modernising science texts and incorporating [[Indian mathematics#Vedic period|vedic mathematics]] into the [[syllabus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/who-is-rajnath-singh/1/247240.html |title=Who is Rajnath Singh? : India, News|work=India Today |date=23 January 2013 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> In April 1994, he was elected into the [[Rajya Sabha]] (Upper House of the [[Parliament of India|Parliament]]) and he became involved with the Advisory committee on Industry (1994\u201396), Consultative Committee for the Ministry of Agriculture, Business Advisory Committee, House Committee and the Committee on Human Resource Development.<ref name=\"profile\"/> On 25 March 1997, he became the President of the BJP's unit in Uttar Pradesh and in 1999 he became the Union Cabinet Minister for Surface Transport.<ref name=\"profile\" />\n\n=== Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh ===\nIn 2000, he became [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|Chief Minister]] of Uttar Pradesh and was twice elected as MLA from [[Haidergarh (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Haidergarh]] in 2001 and 2002.<ref name=\"rediff1\" /> He tried to rationalise the reservation structure in government jobs by introducing the most Backward Classes among the OBC and SC, so that the benefit of reservation can reach the lowest status of Society.<ref name=achieve>[http://www.rajnathsingh.in/achievements/ \"Achievements\"]. rajnathsingh.in</ref>\n\nOn 7 February 2001, Singh inaugurated the [[DND Flyway]] which connects Delhi to Noida.<ref>{{cite news |title='Noida jinx' to keep Akhilesh Yadav away from PM event |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/noida-jinx-to-keep-akhilesh-yadav-away-from-pm-event/articleshow/50372875.cms |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Union Agriculture Minister ===\nIn 2003, Singh was appointed as the [[Ministry of Agriculture & Farmers Welfare|Minister of Agriculture]] and subsequently for Food Processing in the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|NDA]] Government led by [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], and was faced with the difficult task of maintaining one of the most volatile areas of India's economy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2003/06/11/stories/2003061100100800.htm|title=Courage, Mr Rajnath Singh|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=11 June 2003}}</ref> During this period he initiated a few epoch-making projects including the Kisan Call Centre and Farm Income Insurance Scheme.<ref>[http://wikimapia.org/16811689/Shri-Rajnath-Singh-MP-Loksabh-Ghaziabad-Ex-CM-Uattar-pardesh-1-30-Raj-Nagra \"Shri Rajnath Singh, MP (Ghaziabad)\"]. wikimapia.org</ref> He brought down interest rates on Agriculture loans and also established Farmer Commission and initiated Farms Income Insurance Scheme.<ref name=achieve/>\n\n=== BJP President ===\nAfter the BJP lost power in the [[2004 Indian general election|2004 general elections]], it was forced to sit in the Opposition. After the resignation of prominent figure [[Lal Krishna Advani]], and the murder of strategist [[Pramod Mahajan]], Singh sought to rebuild the party by focusing on the most basic [[Hindutva]] ideologies.<ref name=\"instinct\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-12-23/india/27815843_1_rajnath-singh-uniform-civil-code-bjp-national-executive|title=It's basic instinct for Rajnath Singh|work=[[The Times of India]] | first1=Lopamudra|last1=Ghatak|date=23 December 2006}}</ref> He announced his position of \"no compromise\" in relation to the building of a [[Ram Janmabhoomi|Ram Temple]] in [[Ayodhya]] at any cost<ref name=\"instinct\" /> and commended the rule of Vajpayee as Prime Minister, pointing towards all the developments the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|NDA]] made for the ordinary people of India.<ref>[http://indianewsdiary.com/?p=8951 Rajnath Singh is new BJP President] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140311070147/http://indianewsdiary.com/?p=8951 |date=11 March 2014 }}. indianewsdiary.com</ref> He also criticised the role of the English language in India, claiming that most of Indian population is unable to participate in Indian economy and cultural discourse due to extreme preferences shown to English at the expense of native languages.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/BJP-chief-claims-English-bad-for-India-triggers-outrage/articleshow/21178996.cms \"BJP chief claims English bad for India, triggers outrage.\"] ''The Times of India''. 20 July 2013</ref>\n\nHe became the BJP National President on 31 December 2005, a post he held till 19 December 2009. In May 2009, he was elected MP from Ghaziabad in Uttar Pradesh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/Shri%20Rajnath%20Singh%20Biodata_English.pdf|title=Ministry of Home Affairs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606031010/http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/Shri%20Rajnath%20Singh%20Biodata_English.pdf|archive-date=6 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2013, following the resignation of [[Nitin Gadkari]] due to corruption charges, Singh was re-elected as the BJP's National President.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Press Trust of India |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-12-19/india/28067924_1_rajnath-singh-nitin-gadkari-bjp-president |title=Rajnath steps down, Gadkari takes over as BJP president |work=The Times of India |date=19 December 2009 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nSingh is on record shortly after the law [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]] was re-instated in 2013, claiming that his party is \"unambiguously\" in favour of the law, also claiming that \"We will state (at an all-party meeting if it is called) that we support Section 377 because we believe that homosexuality is an unnatural act and cannot be supported.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1131214/jsp/nation/story_17679913.jsp#.VROkUJOUeHw|title=BJP comes out, vows to oppose homosexuality|last=Rameshan|first=Radhika|date=13 December 2011|website=The Telegraph|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe contested the 2014 Lok Sabha elections from [[Lucknow (Lok Sabha constituency)|Lucknow]] constituency and was subsequently elected as a [[Member of Parliament (India)|Member of the Parliament]].<ref name=\"the hindu\">[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/rajnath-singh-surpasses-vajpayees-victory-margin-in-lucknow/article6021382.ece \"Rajnath Singh surpasses Vajpayee\u2019s victory margin in Lucknow\"]. ''The Hindu''. 18 May 2014</ref>\n\n=== Union Home Minister ===\n[[File:The Union Home Minister, Shri Rajnath Singh reviewing the working of the Border Security Force, in New Delhi (1).jpg|thumb|The Union Home Minister, Shri Rajnath Singh reviewing the working of the Border Security Force, in New Delhi]]\nHe was appointed the [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Union Minister of Home Affairs]] in the [[Narendra Modi]] [[First Modi ministry|government]] and was sworn in on 26 May 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmindia.gov.in/en/news_updates/portfolios-of-the-union-council-of-ministers-2/|title=Portfolios of the Union Council of Ministers|website=www.pmindia.gov.in|accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe triggered controversy amid the protests over the police action at [[Jawaharlal Nehru University, Delhi|Jawaharlal Nehru University]] (JNU), on 14 February 2016, claiming that the \"JNU incident\" was supported by [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] chief Hafiz Saeed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/rajnath-singh-hafiz-saeed-let-jnu-protests-had-support-of-let-chief-hafiz-saeed-rajnath-singh/|title=Understand the reality\u2026 Lashkar chief Hafiz Saeed backed JNU incident: Home Minister Rajnath Singh|date=15 February 2016|accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, he claimed that infiltration from Pakistan declined by 52% in a period of two years.<ref>{{citation |title=Narendra Modi's 56-inch chest not reduced an inch: Rajnath Singh |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/280516/narendra-modi-s-56-inch-chest-not-reduced-an-inch-rajnath-singh.html |work=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |date=28 May 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2017, he launched [[Bharat Ke Veer]] Web portal and Application with Bollywood actor [[Akshay Kumar]]. This was an initiative taken by him for the welfare of Martyrs' family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=160767|title=Shri Rajnath Singh inaugurates Web Portal 'Bharat ke Veer'|website=pib.nic.in|access-date=11 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn official anthem was launched on 20 January 2018 for the cause '[[Bharat Ke Veer]]' by him along with film star [[Akshay Kumar]], and other ministers [[Kiren Rijiju]], [[Hansraj Gangaram Ahir|Hansraj Ahir]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/akshay-kumar-rajnath-singh-unveil-official-anthem-of-bharat-ke-veer/articleshow/62581609.cms|title=Akshay Kumar, Rajnath Singh unveil official anthem of 'Bharat Ke Veer'|date=20 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn  21 May 2018, he commissioned [[Bastariya Battalion]]. As Union Home Minister, Rajnath Singh attended the passing out parade of 241 Bastariya Battalion of [[Central Reserve Police Force|CRPF]] in Ambikapur, Chhattisgarh on 21 May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/first-ever-passing-out-parade-of-bastariya-battalion-held-in-chhattisgarh-1238057-2018-05-21|title=First ever graduation parade of 'Bastariya Battalion' held in Chhattisgarh|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=6 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Union Defence Minister===\n[[File:Defence Minister Rajnath Singh commissions INS Khanderi at Mumbai (7).jpg|thumb|Defence Minister Rajnath Singh commissions INS Khanderi at Mumbai]]\nSingh became the [[Minister of Defence (India)|Defence minister]] of India on 31 May  2019.<ref>{{citation |title=PM Modi allocates portfolios. Full list of new ministers |url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/news/pm-modi-allocates-portfolios-full-list-of-new-ministers-1559288502067.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=31 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<center><gallery widths=\"220\" heights=\"200\"> \nFile:The Union Home Minister, Shri Rajnath Singh calling on the President of Nepal, Ms. Bidya Devi Bhandari, in New Delhi on April 18, 2017.jpg|The Union Home Minister, Shri Rajnath Singh calling on the President of Nepal, Ms. Bidya Devi Bhandari, in New Delhi on 18 April 2017 \nFile:Rajnathsingh&meghraj.jpg|Rajnath Singh & Meghraj \nFile:Rajnath singh nayagaon saran aug 2015.jpg|Rajnath Singh addressing a rally in [[Nayagaon, Bihar|Nayagaon]], Sonpur in 2015\nFile:The Union Home Minister, Shri Rajnath Singh meeting the Chairman of Communist Party of Nepal, Shri Khadga Prasad Oli (KP Oli), in Kathmandu on September 19, 2014.jpg|Rajnath Singh meeting Prime Minister of Nepal Khadga Prasad Oli\n</gallery></center> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://164.100.47.194/Loksabha/Members/MemberBioprofile.aspx?mpsno=4268 Biography Profile] at Lok Sabha, Parliament of India\n* [http://rajnathsingh.in/ Official website] (personal)\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Offices and distinctions\n|list1= \n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|in-upr}}\n{{s-bef|before=N/A}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Rajya Sabha]] [[List of Rajya Sabha members from