rs of India}}\n{{Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party chief ministers|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Rajnath}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:15th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:16th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Agriculture Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Chief ministers from Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Deen Dayal Upadhyay Gorakhpur University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Internal Affairs of India]]\n[[Category:Narendra Modi ministry]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 1977\u20131980]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 1997\u20132002]]\n[[Category:People from Chandauli district]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Varanasi]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ghaziabad]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Lucknow]]\n[[Category:17th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Alliance candidates in the 2019 Indian general election]]\n[[Category:Defence Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh members]]\n", "name_user": "MN Shenoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChief Minister of Uttar Pradesh", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rajnath_Singh"}
{"title_page": "Cosmo Kyrle Bellew", "text_new": "'''Cosmo Kyrle Bellew''' (November 23, 1874 (or 1886)\u2013January 25, 1948) was a British/American film actor.\n\nBellew, the son of noted [[silent film]] actor [[Kyrle Bellew]] and Alice Racketrow, was born in London, England.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cosmo Kyrle Bellew |url=https://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?indiv=1&dbid=60901&h=9527384&tid=&pid=&usePUB=true&_phsrc=oDN1692&_phstart=successSource |website=U.S., Social Security Applications and Claims Index, 1936-2007 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020}}</ref> He began his career as a [[vaudeville]] actor, appearing in ''The Devil's Mate'' in 1915.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vaudeville at Hip all Summer |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/45556293/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Reading News-Times |date=June 21, 1915}}</ref>\n\nIn 1917 he enlisted in the British Army in [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Victor of Boelke left Montreal as an Artillery Man |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/419639905/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Gazette, Montreal |date=14 Jun 1917}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the war he continued his career in theater, appearing in the Vaudeville skit ''Somewhere in France'' in 1918, when he was stranded in [[Omaha, Nebraska]] by the [[Spanish Flu]], and was reduced to working in a meat-packing plant and subsisting on free meals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Free Meals Served to Stranded Actors |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/466278997/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Sun |date=29 Oct 1919}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=At the Theaters |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/634433163/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=10 Apr 2020 |agency=Fort Worth Star-Telegram |date=3 Mar 1919}}</ref> He appeared in the musicals ''Dearie''<ref>{{cite news |title=One New Play to be Shown |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/170838257/ |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=Philadelphia Inquirer |date=10 Oct 1920}}</ref> and ''The Canary'' in 1920,<ref>{{cite news |title=\"The Canary\" |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/326551518/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Buffalo Enquirer |date=27 Jan 1920}}</ref> and ''The Boy'' and ''Good Morning Judge\" in 1921,<ref>{{cite news |title=\"The Boy\" will be at Russell |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/456389786/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=10 Apr 2020 |agency=The Citizen |date=19 Feb 1921}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Good Morning Judge |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/253023276/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=10 Apr 2020 |agency=The Binghamton Press |date=28 Jan 1921}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926 he appeared on stage in the [[Ziegfeld]] musical ''Louie the Fourteenth'',<ref>{{cite news |title=\"Louie\" at Werba's |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/557220427/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Brooklyn Daily Times |date=19 Jan 1926}}</ref> and the [[Fox Film]] ''[[Summer Bachelors]]'' (as Bachelor No. 3).<ref>{{cite news |last1=McGowen |first1=Roscoe |title=\"Summer Bachelors\" fills Capitol with Gay Sounds |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/411514379/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=Daily News |date=21 Dec 1926}}</ref>\n\nIn 1927 he moved to Los Angeles and signed with [[Sam Goldwyn]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Cosmo Bellew Signs |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/380567256/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Los Angeles Times |date=5 Mar 1927}}</ref> In 1928 he appeared in ''[[Hit of the Show]]'', starring [[Joe E. Brown]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Musical Comedy Star in Picture |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/622276442/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Pasadena Post |date=15 Dec 1928}}</ref> and ''[[The Bellamy Trial]]'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Filmograms |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/618537409/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Evening Star |date=15 Apr 1928}}</ref> and ''[[The Magic Flame]]'' starring [[Ronald Colman]] and [[Vilma Banky]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Now at Savoy |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/107060659/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Courier-Journal |date=26 Jul 1928}}</ref> and ''[[Man, Woman and Sin]]'', which starred [[John Gilbert (actor)|John Gilbert]].<ref>{{cite news |title=John Gilbert at Strand |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/49733236/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Tribune |date=12 Jan 1928}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nIn 1925 he married Anita Blun in [[Greenwich, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Anita Blun |url=https://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?indiv=1&dbid=70865&h=90110487&tid=&pid=&usePUB=true&_phsrc=oDN1701&_phstart=successSource |website=Connecticut Marriage Records, 1897-1968 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020}}</ref> Bellew died in Beverly hills on January 25, 1948, and Anita passed away on May 15, 1960.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/458727025/?terms=%22anita%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=San Francisco Examiner |date=19 May 1960}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "'''Cosmo Kyrle Bellew''' (November 23, 1874 (or 1886)\u2013January 25, 1948) was a British/American film actor.\n\nBellew, the son of noted [[silent film]] actor [[Kyrle Bellew]] and Alice Racketrow, was born in London, England.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cosmo Kyrle Bellew |url=https://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?indiv=1&dbid=60901&h=9527384&tid=&pid=&usePUB=true&_phsrc=oDN1692&_phstart=successSource |website=U.S., Social Security Applications and Claims Index, 1936-2007 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020}}</ref> He began his career as a [[vaudeville]] actor, appearing in ''The Devil's Mate'' in 1915.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vaudeville at Hip all Summer |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/45556293/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Reading News-Times |date=June 21, 1915}}</ref>\n\nIn 1917 he enlisted in the British Army in [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Victor of Boelke left Montreal as an Artillery Man |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/419639905/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Gazette, Montreal |date=14 Jun 1917}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the war he continued his career in theater, appearing in the Vaudeville skit ''Somewhere in France'' in 1918, when he was stranded in [[Omaha, Nebraska]] by the [[Spanish Flu]], and was reduced to working in a meat-packing plant and subsisting on free meals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Free Meals Served to Stranded Actors |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/466278997/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Sun |date=29 Oct 1919}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=At the Theaters |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/634433163/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=10 Apr 2020 |agency=Fort Worth Star-Telegram |date=3 Mar 1919}}</ref> He appeared in the musicals ''Dearie''<ref>{{cite news |title=One New Play to be Shown |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/170838257/ |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=Philadelphia Inquirer |date=10 Oct 1920}}</ref> and ''The Canary'' in 1920,<ref>{{cite news |title=\"The Canary\" |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/326551518/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020 |agency=The Buffalo Enquirer |date=27 Jan 1920}}</ref> and ''The Boy'' and ''Good Morning Judge\" in 1921,<ref>{{cite news |title=\"The Boy\" will be at Russell |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/456389786/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=10 Apr 2020 |agency=The Citizen |date=19 Feb 1921}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Good Morning Judge |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/253023276/?terms=%22cosmo%2Bbellew%22 |accessdate=10 Apr 2020 |agency=The Binghamton Press |date=28 Jan 1921}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926 he appeared on stage in the [[Ziegfeld]] mus